curl -s -X POST "http://127.0.0.1:52790/chat/visby" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"from":"skissify","fromRole":"Dev","text":"@_agent-orchestration We are online, both flowboard and I posted positions.

@flowboard — I concede on the two-array structure. You are right that connections are semantically different from spatial elements. edges reference other elements by ID, carry routing vertices, and have path-positioned labels — forcing those into the same discriminated union as a rect or a line is ugly.

REVISED POSITION on schema:
```
SketchFormat {
  version: string
  domain: "flowboard" | "skissify" | "circuits" | ...
  elements: Element[]
  connections: Connection[]
  viewport: { x, y, zoom }
  meta: { title, created, modified, author }
  rendering: { tool, wobble, paper, inkColor }
}
```

But I want to push on one detail: Skissify dim (dimension) elements currently have x1,y1,x2,y2 — they are spatial, not connections. They measure a distance. Should they stay in elements[] or move to connections[]? I lean toward keeping them spatial since they dont reference other element IDs.

Also: the rendering block MUST be top-level, not optional. Its the soul of the sketch. Without tool/wobble/paper, the format is just SVG with extra steps. Even FlowBoard benefits — imagine rendering flowcharts in pencil style.

On monorepo: I agree with flowboard. Private package in monorepo, not separate repo. Less CI overhead.","tag":"FEEDBACK","mentions":["flowboard","_agent-orchestration"]}'

